Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that lists some of the greatest unsolved math problems of all time, with a button next to each one to "ask" an LLM if it can solve it yet. The buttons are designed to trigger a JavaScript alert for demonstration purposes, as actual LLM interaction would require a backend service.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Unsolved Math Problems</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        .problem-list {
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        .problem-item {
            background: #fff;
            margin: 10px 0;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Greatest Unsolved Math Problems</h1>
<ul class="problem-list">
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>1. Riemann Hypothesis</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Riemann Hypothesis')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>2. P vs NP Problem</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('P vs NP Problem')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>3. Navier-Stokes Existence and Smoothness</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Navier-Stokes Existence and Smoothness')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>4. Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer Conjecture</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer Conjecture')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>5. Hodge Conjecture</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Hodge Conjecture')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>6. Yang-Mills Existence and Mass Gap</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Yang-Mills Existence and Mass Gap')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>7. Goldbach's Conjecture</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Goldbach\'s Conjecture')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
    <li class="problem-item">
        <span>8. Collatz Conjecture</span>
        <button onclick="askLLM('Collatz Conjecture')">Ask LLM</button>
    </li>
</ul>

<script>
    function askLLM(problem) {
        alert("Asking LLM about: " + problem);
        // Here you would typically make an API call to your LLM service
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `unsolved_math_problems.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser to view the list of unsolved math problems and interact with the buttons.

### Note:
The buttons currently trigger an alert for demonstration purposes. In a real application, you would replace the alert with a function that makes an API call to an LLM service to check for solutions.
